<p>
@EM{{@HI{{dake}}}} follows nouns and quantifiers and means "that's all" or "only".

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ano@KJ{{before^life}}niha@KJ{{one^degrees}}@EM{{dake}}@KJ{{meeting}}imashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I met that professor only once.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@EM{{@HI{{dake}}}} can also be used after a verb or an adjective. In this case it creates a predicate.

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{morning}}ha@KT{{ko-hi-}}wo@KJ{{one^cupfuls^drink}}mu@EM{{dake}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      In the morning I just drink a cup of coffee and that's all.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kono@KJ{{hon}}ha@KJ{{tall}}i@EM{{dake}}deomoshirokunai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      This book is just expensive and not interesting.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
When @EM{{@HI{{dake}}}} follows a noun, the particle used with that
noun can precede or follow @EM{{@HI{{dake}}}}, except for @HI{{ga}}
and @HI{{wo}}, which can optionally be used only after @EM{{@HI{{dake}}}}.
</p>

<p>
